Prompt/Dataset

I have selected the following challenge from TidyTuesday regarding commonly used poor passwords:

https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/main/data/2020/2020-01-14/readme.md

Let’s look at a preview of the underlying dataset:

## # A tibble: 6 × 9
##    rank password category    value time_unit offline_crack_sec rank_alt strength
##   <dbl> <chr>    <chr>       <dbl> <chr>                 <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1     1 password password-r…  6.91 years           2.17               1        8
## 2     2 123456   simple-alp… 18.5  minutes         0.0000111          2        4
## 3     3 12345678 simple-alp…  1.29 days            0.00111            3        4
## 4     4 1234     simple-alp… 11.1  seconds         0.000000111        4        4
## 5     5 qwerty   simple-alp…  3.72 days            0.00321            5        8
## 6     6 12345    simple-alp…  1.85 minutes         0.00000111         6        4
## # ℹ 1 more variable: font_size <dbl>

Each observation pertains to a single password, the type of password (e.g., an animal or alphanumeric string), and strength metrics. value here denotes the online crack time with a corresponding time_unit (e.g., days/years). Online crack time helps convey an asymptotic bound on the time for a computer to brute-force a password over the wire. This is a more practical measurement, since it reflects the time it takes to authenticate over the web, and then receive a response (I am using this for my analysis). Conversely, the offline crack time (offline_crack_sec column) is a strategy that does not require the application to be running. Typically, around 95 possible characters can be used to form a password. Combinatorially, it would take roughly \(95^n\) possible attempts to brute-force any password of length \(n\). Depending on how long each attempt takes, the results are astronomic. Note that each observation is assigned a general password strength level.

Brainstorming

I want a visual that conveys the relative time-to-crack of any passwords that the viewer would instinctively like to compare. Consider a loading screen for a video game or a download, with an animated progress bar. This will provide a sense of scale, relaying paradigms for producing robust passwords to the user. Some obstacles come to mind. How can we dynamically create an animated visual based on user input? How can we account for the drastic variation in time-scale between each observation? First, I anticipate leveraging some of R’s gif-processing libraries, coupled with gganimate to produce an animation for a bar-plot that gradually fills up until the observed online crack time. This gif can be cached for speed, and dynamically update if the inputs change. For the latter, I can normalize the crack time into seconds. Some values will be astronomically large (say if it’s in years for insanely strong passwords), so I can simply take log(time + 1) to smoothen these out.

Analyzing Existing Responses

Example 1

This donut visual is visually stunning. Each arc-section conveys the proportion of the total number of observations in each password category, indicated by arc-length and the percentage. Each category has a color and label. Additionally, every observation is listed along the circle, and manages to fit the arc, a detail that I appreciate a lot. However, the visual lacks any metrics data to convey the effectiveness of passwords between these categories, and the listed passwords are difficult to see, mere providing proportion. I would amend to this visual by providing an interactive zoom feature to pinpoint specific passwords.

Example 2

This visual uses a different method to convey similar information as the last. Instead of a dendogram donut, we have a simple bar-plot, the height of which conveys the relative size of each category (i.e. number of passwords featured). Similarly, the text labels are for stylistic purposes instead of readability, stacked to convey the height of each class. The most popular password (perhaps by highest rank) is highlighted and displayed at the top of each bar–a feature I would add to my repertoire. My criticism for the last one stands: we get a sense of frequency, but not of effectiveness.

INSTRUCTIONS

Hit the gear (settings) icon, select any passwords you’d like and click ‘Render’

You can replay the animation on-demand by clicking ‘Render’ again

Take a look at the table, and see if there are any strong passwords from the last batch that you’d like to compare! (hint: use the strength column, already sorted!)

Note: Beware that animating a new plot (when inputs are changed) might take a minute

This bar-plot allows users to select whatever passwords they like and deduce the relative strength of each one within its respective category depending on the time in seconds (on a natural-logarithmic scale) that it takes to crack each one. We can use this to compare the strength of passwords within the same class, or across classes. Users should keep in mind that since values are on a logarithmic scale, higher values indicate that the time-sink for strong passwords is actually exponential relative to x-axis. The visual is a dynamically updated ggplot animation that interpolates the crack-time value across a time-quanta. One challenge for next time is to effectively slow down each bar to convey the exponential nature of the x-axis value to demonstrate how password strength drastically affects the time-to-crack. This would be very difficult to pre-render, since the number of frames would balloon trying to slow down longer bars.
